<h3>Summary of articles that provides solid evidences of gender differences in elected officials agendas shows <strong>Women Are Best Advocate For Women</strong>.
</h3>
<h3>"Communicating Female and Minority Interests Online: A Study 
of Web Site Issue Discussion among Female, Latino, and African American Members of 
Congress."</h3>
<p>Female, Latino, and African American members of the U.S. House of Representatives 
more frequently link the importance of issues to gender and race on their web sites</p>
<h3>"Women and 
Representation: A Different View of the District?"</h3>
<p>A woman who replaces a man in the same U.S. House district sponsors relatively 
more legislation that pertains to women issues.</p>
<h3>"Critical Mass Theory Revisited: The Behavior and Success of 
Token Women in State Legislatures."</h3>
<p>Even in legislatures with a small number of women, those women are generally more 
active in sponsoring legislation with a focus on women interests.</p>
<h3>"The Difference Women Make: The Policy Impact of Women in 
Congress."</h3>
<p>Democratic and moderate Republican congress women are more likely to pursue 
women interests, such as child care and domestic violence.</p>
<h3>"Speaking Out: An Analysis of Democratic and Republican 
Woman-Invoked Rhetoric of the 105th Congress."</h3>
<p>Democratic and Republican women are more likely than men to bring up women or 
women issues in their floor speeches in the U.S. House; and women spend more 
time than men speaking about other women health issues.</p>
<h3>"Representing Women: Sex, Gender and Legislative Behavior in 
Arizona and California."</h3>
<p>Female state legislators in Arizona and California are more likely than men to sponsor 
bills addressing women issues.</p>
<h3>"The Politics of women Rights: Parties, Positions and Change."</h3>
<p>Women in the U.S. House sponsor a greater number of bills that pertain to  
women rights.</p>
<h3>"Representing women Interests in the U.S. House of 
Representatives."</h3>
<p>Electing more women would substantially reduce the possibility that politicians will 
overlook gender-salient issues.</p>
<h3>"A Woman Place is in the House: Campaigning for Congress in the 
Feminist Era."</h3>
<p>Women are more supportive of “women issues” than are male members  
of Congress.</p>
<h3>"The Impact of Women on State Legislative Policies."</h3>
<p>Women serving in states with higher percentages of female state legislators introduce 
a greater number of bills concerning issues pertaining to women, children, and 
families than women in states with fewer female representatives.</p>
<h3>"The Impact of Gender on Activities and Priorities 
of State Legislators."</h3>
<p>Female state legislators are more likely than men to say that bills relating to children, 
families, or women issues are at the top of their legislative priorities. </p>
